* ✨ new type safe hash index and primary/unique key index APIs (#370, #371)
* ☂️ fix multithreading issue in IncrementalCyclePopulator (#366)
* ☂️ fix case where `announced.version` could read an empty file and throw NPE (#367)
* ⚗️ initial release of **experimental** `FlatRecord` API; please avoid using for now (#375)

## Type Safe Indexes

Two new API classes, `HashIndex` and `UniqueKeyIndex`, provide type safety and ergonomic improvements over the index classes in the generated client API.

Given `Movie` and `Actor` models:

```java
@HollowPrimaryKey(field={"videoId"})
class Movie {
  long videoId;
  String title;
  Integer releaseYear;
  Set<Actor> actors;
}

class Actor {
  String name;
}
```

Unique index and lookup by primary key looks like:

```java
// requires `Movie` from generated client API, but doesn't use generated index class

UniqueKeyIndex<Movie, Long> index = UniqueKeyIndex.from(consumer, Movie.class)
    .bindToPrimaryKey()
    .usingPath("videoId", Long.class);
consumer.addRefreshListener(index);

// ...

Movie match = index.findMatch(42L);
```

Hash index and lookup with a *query bean* looks like:

```java
class MovieQuery {
  @FieldPath
  int releaseYear;

  @FieldPath("actors.element.name")
  String actorName;

  // ...
}
```

```java
HashIndex<Movie, MovieQuery> index = HashIndex.from(consumer, Movie.class)
        .usingBean(MovieTitleYearQuery.class);
consumer.addRefreshListener(index);

// ...

Stream<Movie> matches = index.findMatches(new MovieQuery(2016, "Idris Elba"));
```

Absent from the new index classes are `listenToDataRefresh()` and `detatchFromDataRefresh()` methods. Instead, add or remove the index as a refresh listener on the consumer, e.g. `consumer.addRefreshListener(myIndex)` and `consumer.removeRefreshListener(myIndex)`. An index which *isn't added* as a refresh listener won't automatically stay current. Adding an index as a listener to a different consumer than the one it was constructed with is an error.

### Deprecating generated index classes

**NOTE:** The generated `{Type}PrimaryKeyIndex`, `{Type}UniqueKeyIndex`, and `{API}HashIndex` classes will be generated with `@Deprecated` annotations the next time you generate your client API.

## Experimental Flat Records API

This is the beginning work for a stable, supported IncrementalProducer API. The new `FlatRecord` features have a *high probability* of breaking or being removed in the future. We recommend users outside of Netflix avoid using these features until a stable API is announced. No ETA on a stable API.

Though marked as BETA, we're endeavoring to avoid breaking changes to the current `HollowIncrementalProducer` and related classes. The multithreading bugfix mentioned above applies to the BETA incremental producer API.

- #173 fix a bug in calculating the load factor in the ByteArrayOrdinalMap that was causing NegativeSizeArrayException before reaching the max capacity
- #166 explicitly show `[null]` for null members in history and diff UIs
- #171 change `HollowAPIGenerator` to accept a destination path instead of specifying it with each call to `generateFiles`

## HollowAPIGenerator refactor

* added `withDestination(Path)` to the builder
* added no-arg `generateSourceFiles()` and `generateSourceFile(HollowJavaFileGenerator)`
* deprecated `HollowAPIGenerator` constructors that don't accept a destination path
* deprecated `generateFiles(File)` and `generateFile(File, HollowJavaFileGenerator)` file

This helps avoid a bug in subclasses of `HollowAPIGenerator` around the logic that makes the package portion of the destination path optional. The following doesn't work correctly:

```
public void generateFiles(File destination) {
     // this generates source correctly, even if package portion is omitted from destination
    super.generateFiles(destination);

    // this will fail to generate the class in the correct directory if destination omits the package
    // portion of the path
    super.generateFile(destination, new MyGenerator(...));
}
```

Note: deprecated constructor and methods are intended to be removed in Hollow 3.

## Better Support for subclassing producer or consumer builders

Both `HollowProducer.Builder` and `HollowConsumer.Builder` now have type parameters that allow you to write a custom builder subclass that will preserve the fluent API style of calls.

The examples below use a custom subclass of `HollowProducer.Builder`; use the same pattern for subclassing `HollowConsumer.Builder`.

 Prior to `v2.10.0`, the following wouldn't work as desired:

```
// v2.9.9 or before
class CustomProducerBuilder extends HollowProducer.Builder {
  CustomProducerBuilder withSomethingExtra() {
    // ...
    return this;
  }        
}
```

```
HollowProducer producer = new CustomProducerBuilder()
  .withAnnouncer(announcer)
  .withPublisher(publisher)
  .withSomethingExtra() // compile error; method doesn't exist on `HollowProducer.Builder`
  .build();
```

You either had to call all custom methods before calling any inherited builder methods, or abandon the fluent style of calls.

With this release, if you now declare your custom builder subclass as follows, the fluent style will work with builder calls in any order:

```
class CustomProducerBuilder extends HollowProducer.Builder<CustomProducerBuilder> {
  CustomProducerBuilder withSomethingExtra() {
    // ...
    return this;
  }        
}
```
